<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 11-14 mm, female 16-19.5 mm. The triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum places this species in a group together with 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From the latter two species, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs by the absence of golden pile along the anterior and lateral margins of the mesoscutum. The species differs from 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum being longer than wide and reaching the anterior half of the mesoscutum. In the male, the ratio vertex width:head width is approximately 1:3.3 (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 13–18" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 13 - 18. 13 - 15 Mesoscutum: 13 Peradon aureoscutus male holotype 14 P. aureus male Ecuador CNC 15 P. trivittatus male French Guiana RMNH 16 Peradon fenestratus, scutellum lateral 17, 18 Tergites 2 and 3: 17 Peradon trilinea male holotype 18 P. aureus male holotype." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures13-18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362275" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures13-18">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), and the lateral margins of tergite 2 are more or less parallel in the anterior half and diverging in the posterior 1/2 to 1/3. The female is figured in 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 97–104" captionStartId="F19" captionText="Figures 97 - 104. Dorsal habitus of Peradon species (trivittatus group) 97 P. trivittatus ♂ Suriname RMNH 98 P. trivittatus ♀ Suriname RMNH 99 P. fenestratus ♀ Brazil INPA 100 P. trilinea ♂ holotype 101 P. trilinea ♀ Peru NHMUK 102 P. aureus ♀ holotype 103 P. aureus ♂ Ecuador CNC 104 P. aureoscutus ♂ holotype. Scale bar: 10 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures97-104" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362289" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures97-104">Fig. 102</figureCitation>
. As the female of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unknown, it is uncertain whether the characters described for the males of both species also apply to the females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This taxon is very similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although both taxa were described by F.M. Hull, he apparently was unaware of this similarity, as 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1155/1944/61923" author="Hull, FM" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="22 - 45" refId="B14" refString="Hull, FM, 1944b. Studies on syrphid flies in the Museum of Comparative Zoology. Psyche 51: 22 - 45" title="Studies on syrphid flies in the Museum of Comparative Zoology." url="https://doi.org/10.1155/1944/61923" volume="51" year="1944 b">Hull (1944b)</bibRefCitation>
only noted that it was 'related distantly to 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">beebei</emphasis>
' (a species nowadays placed in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hull, 1937" authorityName="Hull" authorityYear="1937" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pseudomicrodon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudomicrodon" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Pseudomicrodon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hull, 1937).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
